                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d867">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12795a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to Mexico.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-09T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 9, 1914, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Please urgently impress upon Carbajal the folly of resistance. He should not take
                    counsel of the military men who by supporting Huerta’s programme made themselves
                    responsible for existing conditions. Those who have been guilty of conduct which
                    might lead to their punishment should leave the country; others are not likely
                    to suffer. It is of the highest importance that Carbajal should reach an
                    agreement with Carranza immediately. Delay simply multiplies the dangers.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
